The paper discusses the development of multiple models of varying fidelity for Cyber-Physical Systems (CPS) and the need for a rigorous notion of conformance between different models and between models and their implementations. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of mathematical analysis, control synthesis, and simulation, which are all related to the Embedded Systems (cs.ET) sub-category. The paper also proposes an algorithm for detecting non-conformance, which is related to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of proven tools, which suggests that it may belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the definition of a universal notion of conformance, which is related to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category.
